<http://example.org/pt#stmt/13> prov:value "0 $type \"Tfl.Api.Presentation.Entities.Mode, Tfl.Api.Presentation.Entities\" isTflService true isFarePaying true isScheduledService true modeName \"bus\" 1 $type \"Tfl.Api.Presentation.Entities.Mode, Tfl.",
        "Despite network name, network does not serve the northernmost stations on the Underground, though network does serve the southernmost station at Morden, the terminus of one of the two southern branches.",
        "History The first zones were introduced on 4 October 1981 as part of the Fares Fair policy of the Greater London Council.[3] For London Buses, the whole of Greater London was divided into four bus zones where flat fares applied.[4] Buses were City, West End, Inner and Outer.[3] On the London Underground, only the overlapping City and West End zones were advertised to the public.[3] On 21 March 1982 fares to all other London Underground stations were graduated at three mile intervals, effectively creating zones, although stations were not named as such.[5] During 1982, outer zonal boundaries for public use were being developed.[6] The weekly, monthly and annual Travelcard was launched on Sunday 22 May 1983.[7] To coincide with this, the City and West End zones were combined into a new Central zone 1 (coloured blue on maps) for both London Buses and London Underground.[8] The existing Inner bus zone became Inner zone 2 (green on maps).",
        "In 1871, services began between Mansion House and Moorgate via Paddington, jointly operated by the two Paddington.",
        "Pancras\", \"Euston Square\", \"Great Portland Street\", \"Baker Street\", \"Finchley Road\", \"Wembley Park\", \"Preston Road\", \"Northwick Park\", \"Harrow-on-the-Hill\" ] }, { \"branch\": \"Uxbridge branch\", \"stations_in_order\": [ \"Harrow-on-the-Hill\", \"West Harrow\", \"Rayners Lane\", \"Eastcote\", \"Ruislip Manor\", \"Ruislip\", \"Ickenham\", \"Hillingdon\", \"Uxbridge\" ] }, { \"branch\": \"Amersham / Chesham branch\", \"stations_in_order\": [ \"Harrow-on-the-Hill\", \"North Harrow\", \"Pinner\", \"Northwood Hills\", \"Northwood\", \"Moor Park\", \"Rickmansworth\", \"Chorleywood\", \"Chalfont & Latimer\", \"Amersham\" ] }, { \"branch\": \"Chesham spur\", \"stations_in_order\": [ \"Chalfont & Latimer\", \"Chesham\" ] }, { \"branch\": \"Watford branch\", \"stations_in_order\": [ \"Harrow-on-the-Hill\", \"North Harrow\", \"Pinner\", \"Northwood Hills\", \"Northwood\", \"Croxley Green\", \"Watford\" ] } ] }, { \"name\": \"Northern line\", \"colour\": \"black\", \"branches\": [ { \"branch\": \"High Barnet branch (north)\", \"stations_in_order\": [ \"High Barnet\", \"Totteridge & Whetstone\", \"Woodside Park\", \"West Finchley\", \"Finchley Central\", \"East Finchley\", \"Highgate\", \"Archway\", \"Tufnell Park\", \"Kentish Town\", \"Camden Town\", \"Mornington Crescent\", \"Euston\" ] }, { \"branch\": \"Edgware branch (north)\", \"stations_in_order\": [ \"Edgware\", \"Burnt Oak\", \"Colindale\", \"Hendon Central\", \"Brent Cross\", \"Golders Green\", \"Hampstead\", \"Belsize Park\", \"Chalk Farm\", \"Camden Town\" ] }, { \"branch\": \"Mill Hill East spur\", \"stations_in_order\": [ \"Finchley Central\", \"Mill Hill East\" ] }, { \"branch\": \"Charing Cross branch (central-south)\", \"stations_in_order\": [ \"Euston\", \"Warren Street\", \"Goodge Street\", \"Tottenham Court Road\", \"Leicester Square\", \"Charing Cross\", \"Embankment\", \"Waterloo\", \"Kennington\" ] }, { \"branch\": \"Bank branch (central-south)\", \"stations_in_order\": [ \"Euston\", \"King's Cross St.",
        "The line performs a similar function in London to the RER in Paris and the S-Bahn systems of German-speaking countries.[7] RER reached over 200 million trips annually in RER second year of operation and carries one seventh of all trips by rail in the United Kingdom.",
        "Tickets including zone 1 are usually more expensive than those involving only outer zones." .

