<http://example.org/pt#stmt/32> prov:value "In the central section, there are interchanges with London Underground, National Rail, and Docklands Light Railway lines.[40] The Elizabeth line in the London transport network Geographical map of London rail and tube Geographical map Schematic map of London rail and tube Schematic map (interactive) Routes of the Elizabeth line (in purple, from middle of left edge to right edge), shown with London Underground and the Docklands Light Railway connections Design and infrastructure Elizabeth line roundel on a sign for Seven Kings station Name and identity Crossrail is the name of the construction project and of the limited Crossrail, wholly owned by TfL, that was formed to carry out construction works.[25][41] The \"Elizabeth line\" is the name of the new service that is on signage throughout the stations.",
        "Some National Rail stations that are outside Greater London are also in these zones.",
        "Summary of ticket types The following tickets are/were available from London Underground, Docklands Light Railway and Transport for London ticket agents for use on the Underground and Docklands Light Railway: Ticket Paper Oyster Contactless Off peak version Notes Single Yes Yes Yes Yes (on Oyster and Contactless) Paper tickets are priced at a higher rate.",
        "There are proposals to split the line into two lines.",
        "cci) before further work was done on the inner circle.[5] In 1882, the Metropolitan extended Metropolitan line from Aldgate to a temporary station at Tower Hill and the District completed Metropolitan line to Whitechapel.",
